statement:
Let \emph{PA = LU} be

\begin{align*}\begin{bmatrix}
1 &0 &0 \\ 
0& 0 &1 \\ 
0& 1 &0 
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
1& 0 &2 &3 \\ 
2& 1 & 8 & 8\\ 
0& 1& 4 & 2
\end{bmatrix}
= \begin{bmatrix}
1& 0 &0 \\ 
0& 1& 0\\ 
2& 1 & 1
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}
1 &0 &2 &3 \\ 
0& 1 & 4 &2 \\ 
0& 0 &0 &0 
\end{bmatrix}\end{align*}

and

\begin{align*}b = \begin{bmatrix}
b_1 \\ b_2 \\ b_3
\end{bmatrix}\end{align*}

\textbf{(b)} Find the condition on \emph{b\textsubscript{1}},
\emph{b\textsubscript{2}}, and \emph{b\textsubscript{3}} so that
\emph{Ax = b} has at least one solution.
